{{Infobox university |name = Leland Powers School |image_name = |image_size = |caption = |motto = |mottoeng = |established = 1904 |closed = 1979 |type = [[Private university|Private]] |affiliation = |endowment = |president = [[Leland Powers]] |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |other = |city = [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] |state = [[Massachusetts]] |country = [[United States]] |coor = |campus = |former_names = School of Elocution (1879-1943) |sports = |colors = |nickname = |mascot = |athletics = |affiliations = |website = |logo = |footnotes = }} The '''Leland Powers School''', also known as the '''Leland Powers School of Communication''', '''Leland Powers School of Radio, Theatre, and Television''', '''Leland Powers Theatre School''', the '''Leland Powers School of Expression''', '''Leland Powers School of the Spoken Word''', and originally called the '''Leland Powers School of Elocution''', was originally located in the [[Fenway–Kenmore|Fenway neighborhood]] of [[Boston, Massachusetts]], and later in [[Brookline, Massachusetts]]. Speaker and author [[Leland Powers]] founded the school in 1904.<ref>Hesperides. (2007) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=DlW4BN70woYC&dq A Handbook of American Private Schools]''. Read Books. p 236. {{ISBN|978-1406766318}}</ref> The school educated several notable speakers and authors of the early 20th century, including drama educator [[T. Earl Pardoe]], actress [[Reta Shaw]], and journalist [[Wendall Woodbury]].<ref name=Tibbetts>Tibbetts, M.M. (1954) ''Random recollections: Commemorating the 50th anniversary of Leland Powers School, 1904-1954''. Boston: Leland Powers School.</ref>
== History == [[Leland T. Powers]] founded the school after teaching with the [[Redpath Lyceum Bureau]], a [[Chautauqua]] circuit business. While working for the bureau, Powers was assigned as a reader during chautauquas, and as a coach to other readers. Powers also edited scripts for usage, focusing on readability and performance. During this time Powers was an associate of [[Carl Sandburg]].<ref>Tapia, J.E. (1997) ''Circuit chautauqua: From rural education to popular entertainment in early twentieth century America.'' McFarland. p 66. {{ISBN|978-0786402137}}</ref>
In 1904, Powers' school cost $200 for a semester's tuition.<ref name=Tibbetts/> Joining his wife and more than a dozen staff members in teaching 140 students annually, Powers had a building constructed in 1914 at 31 Evans Way in the [[Fenway–Kenmore|Fenway neighborhood]] next door to the [[Girls' Latin School]].
The School was credited with being on the leading edge of technology when in 1944 it started broadcasting a show called "The Great American Home" on local station [[WIXG]].<ref>Tuttle, Marguerite. (1952) ''A Guide to education for professional careers.'' p 36.</ref>
== Graduates == * [[Fay Davis]], actress * [[Jeff Donnell]], actress * [[Mary Freeman Byrne]], author * Rod Fritz, newscaster, Boston (WBZ and WRKO) and New York (Fox) (as per [[WRKO#Past news and traffic services|this excerpt from the WRKO article]]) * [[Ernest Holmes]], religious leader * [[Don Gillis (sportscaster)|Don Gillis]], sportscaster * Neil MacNevin (Tom Evans), radio/tv announcer (see [[Creature Double Feature]]) * Palmer Payne, newscaster, NYC ([http://donswaim.com/wcbsmem.payne.html anecdote from his days at [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS (880 AM)]]]) * [[Glynn Ross]], opera impresario * [[Bob Wilson (sportscaster)|Bob Wilson]], sportscaster * J T Nichols, playwright (Porktown, Taming the Savages, Jesus & the Pirates, etc.)
